Still used PowerShell a LOT during this time, but had an even greater need to do web request related things and more automation to make my life easier and reduce my suffering.

Fast forward to March 2011, I started as a Web Engineer. First thing I did was automate the hell out of SharePoint. I also learned a lot of C# by reading through our source control and following code paths.
Also want to thank everyone I've become friends with over Windows Phone. That device platform created quite the community and helped make things so damn exciting for the time the platform existed.

I have to personally thank @WithinRafael and @ChrisWalshie, though <3. If ChevronWP7 didn't exist, I probably would've said to hell with WP dev because I wasn't paying $99 just to deploy to my phone. Nope.

I even made the IT Director at the time hook me up with a Samsung Focus THE DAY IT GOT RELEASED. Best believe it was ON. I went all in with it and was on XDA-Developers at the time. Did a whole bunch of cursed stuff that I'm known for.

Back to Windows Phone. I remember discovering this and just losing my mind at how wonderful it was, even in emulator form. I wanted to, NEEDED to develop for it like it was my personal calling. I decided to learn as much as I could through trial/error, tutorials, official docs.

Oh, and I also had my first exposure to SharePoint and SOAP Web Services during this time...

Fast forward to 2010 - "Visual Studio 2010 Express for Windows Phone CTP". That should say enough right there.

It was then that my eyes started GLOWING. I started automating so many things with PowerShell, plugging into SQL, automating VMWare (yes I was a VMWare Admin eventually), creating WinForms GUIs (because why not?), deploying agents, modifying services, all kinds of fun.

Fast forward to Summer 2007, landed an internship at the company I currently work at (15 years in June.. wth is my problem??) and it was for a Tech Architect intern position. I did a lot of automation work and happened to come across PowerShell at this point.

I thought it was pretty cool I could use do this. Assignment finished, spent time over the summer (this was 2006) playing around with it and creating simple WinForms GUIs with it. Didn't actually create an app or anything useful, just playing around with it. Summer over.

My absolute first exposure to .NET actually involved SharpDevelop and I don't even remember how and why I downloaded it, but I ended up using C# for a simple college assignment (I had NO knowledge of it, but I thought it looked enough like C++ to port a sorting alg over).

It's funny when I think back on my exposure to #dotnet and I realize that it was my fate to become a .NET Developer. Although it wasn't my FIRST exposure to .NET, I owe a LOT to #PowerShell for pulling me in (thank you @jsnover).
